<TEXT>
 Eighteen citizen groups today called on the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> to give the public a comprehensive assessment of environmental safety at the government's trouble-plagued nuclear weapons production centers. The groups, led by the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, released a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> urging preparation of a `` programmatic environmental impact statement'' on the entire complex, which involves 17 facilities employing some 100,000 people in 12 states. `` It is time to take the wraps off what has been in effect the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>'s ` Stealth' program and to compel meaningful public scrutiny of its plans for the complex,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reicher </PERSON>, an attorney for the council. The move came one day after the <ORGANIZATION> NRDC </ORGANIZATION> and two other groups filed suit to compel the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to prepare an environmental impact statement on its sprawling <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> plant in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> before any of the three weapons reactors there can be restarted.
