<HEAD>Braves and Falcons Look to Move to the Suburbs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on sports wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When it opened, it was a blue and white miracle in concrete and steel, built in a civic frenzy to bring major league sports to the South. Twenty-three years later, <LOCATION> Atlanta-Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stadium </LOCATION> finds itself a pariah among ballparks, a place that both its tenants _ baseball's <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> and football's <ORGANIZATION> Falcons </ORGANIZATION> _ are desperately trying to flee even before the mortgage is paid off. Grumbling about the stadium has gone on for years. The round configuration is n't perfect for baseball, and for football, everyone agrees, it's worse _ when the rectangular field is fitted in beneath the circular stands, the usually desirable 50-yard-line seats are farthest away from the action. Dirty concourses and disgusting restrooms led some in recent years to dub it `` Atlanta-Filthy County Stadium.'' The quality of the playing field has drawn complaints from <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> players and opposing teams alike. Narrow concourses leave little room for modern concession areas. Still, the downtown stadium is structurally sound, repainted and looking pretty good, although the restrooms can still get unpleasant. But 1988 may be remembered as the beginning of the end for <LOCATION> Atlanta-Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stadium </LOCATION>. Both the <ORGANIZATION> Falcons </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> insist they will not sign up for another hitch after their leases run out in 1990. It is now possible that within the next decade, the city of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, once home to five major-league sports franchises, will be down to one, its once proud stadium bulldozed and the land sold to pay off the debts. `` I do n't enjoy hearing things like that,'' said <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the dynamic mayor of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> from 1961-69 who still boasts of how he and his city built a major league ballpark `` on ground we did n't own, with money we did n't have, for a team we had n't signed. `` I walked around the stadium -LRB- at the Dec. 4 <ORGANIZATION> Falcons </ORGANIZATION> game -RRB- and it was in excellent condition,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said recently. `` It could be used, and be in good shape, for a long time.'' But it appears it wo n't be. In 1986, a civic panel recommended two new stadiums: a domed football arena adjoining the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> World Congress Center convention facility downtown by 1990, and a new baseball park at the present stadium site by'95. In 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Falcons </ORGANIZATION> owner <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, long fed up with a lease that benefits the <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION>, with a lack of luxury boxes and with the stadium itself, said he would not renew it. Since then <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> has, at various times, discussed playing in the proposed `` <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> Dome,'' building an open-air stadium near the team's suburban <LOCATION> Gwinnett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> training complex, 30 miles from downtown <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, and even moving the franchise to football-hungry <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and its 80,000-seat Gator Bowl. The <ORGANIZATION> Falcons </ORGANIZATION> are gone, concedes <PERSON> Reggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, the stadium authority's executive director since April 1987. `` I'd say so. ... I can understand that the football people here need to leave to get into an environment where they can share in other ... revenues.'' Then, earlier this month, <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON> dropped a bombshell: The <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> are n't staying either. The <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION>, he said, are holding `` very serious discussions'' about moving to a proposed state-of-the-art baseball stadium in <LOCATION> Gwinnett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON>, in a recent interview, said detailing the problems with the stadium would take `` a laundry list.'' He mentioned specifically the lack of modern amenities and the round configuration. `` Can you play baseball there? Sure you can,'' <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON> said. `` Can you play football there? Sure you can. `` We just want a better place _ a place that is competitive with the modern-day stadiums, built only for baseball. ... I'm not saying it's unplayable. But we can do better, and if the <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> can, we certainly should pursue that.'' <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON> says the <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> would consider other metro <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> locations, and would probably agree to stay in the current facility until that new downtown baseball stadium _ `` which we were promised, really'' in the 1986 plans _ can be built in the mid-90s. But the proposed $ 159 million football dome remains tangled in financial and political haggling, and the subsequent $ 60 million baseball stadium is not even under serious consideration yet. `` We're interested in getting a new facility,'' <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON> said. `` They -LRB- the city and <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> -RRB- do n't want to talk about that. So there's not much for us to discuss right now.'' That leaves the <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION>, in <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON>'s words, `` very close to getting into substantive, detail-type conversations'' with Gwinnett officials. `` I've been very impressed with the enthusiasm and the spirit I see among the people in <LOCATION> Gwinnett </LOCATION>,'' he said. The idea of the <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Falcons </ORGANIZATION> leaving <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> has yet to spawn a great public outcry. The two teams have made the playoffs in only five out of their 46 combined seasons in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, and cynics suggest the city would n't miss them. And while most <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> officials are backing the dome plan for the <ORGANIZATION> Falcons </ORGANIZATION>, they have n't exactly scurried to keep the <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> in the city limits. <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> City Council President <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Arrington </PERSON>, while accusing the <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> of racism in wanting to move to the white suburbs, said the city would `` welcome other municipalities within our community to shoulder more of the costs'' of pro sports. Both teams could be gone from the stadium by 1991 _ despite the fact that the debts wo n't be paid off until 2000. The city, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said, might wind up selling the land just to pay off the stadium debts: `` The question becomes whether the value of the property is equal to the amount of money owed.'' All of this is a far cry from 1964, when sports in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> meant <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> or minor league baseball's <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crackers </ORGANIZATION>. It was then that ground was broken for the stadium that would propel the city _ literally and figuratively _ into the big leagues. <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stadium </LOCATION>, with <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> at the whip, was built in just 51 weeks, with $ 14 million borrowed from booster-minded bankers. The <ORGANIZATION> Braves </ORGANIZATION> moved from <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> in 1966; the <ORGANIZATION> Falcons </ORGANIZATION> came that fall. Within six years came basketball's <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawks </ORGANIZATION>, who play in The Omni downtown, and hockey's Flames and soccer's <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION>, both since departed. `` Twenty-five years after that stadium was built ... it's paid for itself handsomely, with what it's done for <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> since then,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. `` I certainly would have hoped it would have gone on for a much longer time.'' Sports in the suburbs, he said, `` would be better than not having anything.'' But <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> thinks losing either team to the suburbs would be a blow to the city. `` I think its preferable that they stay in the city of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` That's the core of everything.''
