<HEAD>Analyst Says Grain Imports Put Financial Burden on Soviet Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The higher cash costs of importing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain and soybeans have caused grumbling among the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s financial planners and are contributing to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s huge economic problems, says an Agriculture Department economist For example, in the first nine months of 1988, about $ 1.2 billion worth of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain was shipped to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. In addition, about $ 362 million worth of soybeans and soybean meal was shipped. In all, counting sales by other countries, the Soviets may spend around $ 16.5 billion on imports of agricultural products this calendar year, up about $ 1 billion from 1987, says <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeimetz </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` The bill for grain, the primary farm import for which the Soviets pay hard currency, will increase over $ 1 billion from 1987's $ 2.6 billion, mostly because import prices are up 35 percent,'' she said It is this drain that disturbs <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s planners most. The main source of hard currency for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is from petroleum sales, but oil prices are down and grain prices are up. `` Energy sales to the West usually account for 60 percent of Soviet hard currency receipts,'' <PERSON> Zeimetz </PERSON> said in a recent report. `` Soviet oil export prices in the first nine months of 1988 averaged below 1986. The 15 percent to 20 percent price increase in 1987 was more than lost in 1988.'' <PERSON> Zeimetz </PERSON> said Soviet agricultural import volume in 1989 may be about at the same total level, except that grain imports may be greater. Overall, the cost of imports next year could rise substantially, with grain prices rising by as much as 20 percent, she said. `` The cost of increased agricultural imports _ coupled with relatively low petroleum prices, deteriorating terms of trade, and continued need for non-agricuturl imports _ could make Soviet traders even more exacting in 1989,'' <PERSON> Zeimetz </PERSON> said. Much of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s economic problems stem from a lack of quality food and other consumer goods, massive consumer subsidies for food, and higher wages. As a result, she said, there has been an excess of consumer demand and excess savings, despite both open and hidden inflation. `` The Soviets have maintained the basic prices on most state-distributed foodstuffs at 1962 levels,'' <PERSON> Zeimetz </PERSON> said. `` These have resulted in massive consumer subsidies as production, processing and marketing costs have risen.'' In 1987, the subsidies cost about 60 billion rubles, or $ 94 billion, she said. And they continue to rise. `` Although small cooperatives and individual enterprises are now encouraged, their output of goods and services is not yet significant,'' she said. Meanwhile, the average Soviet's income during the first nine months of 1988 was reported up 9 percent from a year earlier, when the corresponding increase was less than half as much. Deposits in the state savings bank rose 5 percent during the period. <PERSON> Zeimetz </PERSON> said the Soviets `` have built modestly on the 1986 breakthrough in agricultural production, when output increased 7 percent after years of stagnation or decline. Still, per capita production has only regained its 1976-78 average.'' Currently, she said, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s focus is on improving farming practices and management, increasing competition, and raising worker incentives by decentralizing management and financial control. `` Decentralization's newest aim is to establish lease collectives, predominantly on state and collective farms, but also on land outside the socialized farm system,'' <PERSON> Zeimetz </PERSON> said. `` Small groups can lease land from a farm, a government agency or an industrial firm that controls it.'' Although leasing has produced `` phenomenal increases'' in production, efficiency and cost savings, <PERSON> Zeimetz </PERSON> said the results may partly reflect the attention being given the few lease units in operation. <PERSON> Zeimetz </PERSON> said the potential for big gains from leasing is limited by a number of factors: _ Administrator and farm manager resistance to giving up control _ Farm worker reluctance to take risks _ Inadequacies of Soviet farm supplies and infrastructure _ Doubts about the permanence of the lease program _ Lack of prices determined by market demands _ State reluctance to allow large income disparities `` A recent poll showed that only about 15 percent of the adult population favored cooperative and individual labor activities, to which leasing is cl she said. `` Negative attitutes about income disparities have led to vandalism, osely related,'' and are limiting success not only for improved agricultural production but also for food processing and trade, and other consumer goods and services.'' On another front, <PERSON> Zeimetz </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> has tried to improve the storage, processing and distribution of farm commodities in order to improve the quality of food and reduce losses after harvest, which Soviet officials estimate may exceed 25 percent of the harvest. `` Recently, 70 meat processing enterprises had no refrigerators, and of the 850 refrigerators at other enterprises, 42 percent had been in operation for 20 to 50 years,'' she said. `` Less than 20 percent of Soviet processing machinery was up to world standards, and 60 percent was virtually worn <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the instant she crosses the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, returned to <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> to do another sitcom. A few weeks before CBS decided to take her show off the air, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> was interviewed in her trailer parked outside Stage 3 at the <ORGANIZATION> MTM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>, the same trailer she used for `` The <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> Show'' and was also once used by <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Garland </PERSON>. She's on a couch, wearing a red warm-up suit. Her light brown hair is cut stylishly short. Up close, despite her diabetic condition and too many years spent exposing her skin to the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> sun, she looks as good as her bank account. She credits this to a change in lifestyle. She has quit smoking, does light impact aerobics and has adopted a healthier diet. In `` <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> played a woman who works for the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> borough president, has a teen-age son and remarries a structural engineer with a son and daughter. She has a mother -LRB- <PERSON> Eileen </PERSON> <PERSON> Heckart </PERSON> -RRB- who's an ultra-liberal activist, and her new husband -LRB- <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Arndt </PERSON> -RRB- has a father -LRB- <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> -RRB- who's a staunch conservative. The stories were a little different from the usual sitcom fare. In one show she was held up by a man in a wheelchair, then felt obligated to find him a job. In another, her husband admited to having had an affair with his late wife's sister. Once, she had to clear her father-in-law's reputation from an old accusation that food poisoning in his restaurant cost <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> the presidency `` We're breaking a few molds,'' she says. `` We do some outlandish things and conduct ourselves like adults having a great time.'' It was <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s first one-camera show without an audience since she displayed only her legs as `` Sam'' on `` <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON>, Private Detective,'' in 1959.
