<HEAD>In Eighty Eight, '88 Was the Year of Drought and Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EIGHTY EIGHT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was Eighty Eight's year in'88, when the little farm town with the numerical name found its moment in the spotlight as calendars flipped to 8-8-88. But once Aug. 9 dawned, Eighty Eight got back to the everyday life of'88. And, as in thousands of small towns from coast to coast, 1988 was a year for drought, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the timeless rhythms of rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Eighty Eight has neat houses, a grocery, a tire company and two churches stretching about a mile along a two-lane highway. Its 200 residents have no local government, no school, not even a traffic light _ nothing, in short, that would be likely to attract attention. But for a few heady days in August, when the television networks and newspapers and magazines were dispatching reporters and photographers, and thousands of tourists were trooping to town, it seemed the whole world was peeking in on Eighty Eight. `` That was a right exciting thing for this little area,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickerson </PERSON>, whose family's lumber mill is the largest local employer. It was also a right unlikely thing. Local residents welcomed all comers with an `` 88 Celebration'' on Aug. 7 and 8. They put on a parade with an 88-year-old grand marshal and cut a cake 8 feet, 8 inches long. They crowded in front of <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> McPherson </PERSON>'s 88 Market and shouted, `` Good Morning, America!'' for <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>. They staged The Wedding of the Century for a <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> couple _ <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Accardo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhlbeier </PERSON> _ at 8:08 p.m. on Aug. 8. Twenty-six thousand pieces of mail got the 8-8-88 postmark. Letters still arrive at the closet-size post office in one corner of the grocery. But for the most part, `` everything is just real quiet around here,'' said <PERSON> Donnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacon </PERSON>, the postmistress. `` I'd say in a week everything got back pretty much to normal. That is to say Eighty Eight got back to dairy and tobacco farming, conservative politics and lunch-hour crowds at the 88 Market, where Ms. <PERSON> McPherson </PERSON> still serves up hot meals or cold cuts to the <ORGANIZATION> Dickerson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lumber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> gang and other regulars. It remains a pleasant, unpretentious community. `` People still eat bologna sandwiches,'' said <PERSON> Dickerson </PERSON>. `` I know I do.'' Before and after the TV cameras came and went, Eighty Eight mirrored rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. In the spring, crops were planted and herds were turned out and folks in surrounding <LOCATION> Barren </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>'s No. 1 dairy producer, looked toward summer. But the rains stopped the first of June, pastures dried up and hay that had been stored for winter feeding had to be hauled out months early. In the fall, hopes rose with the excellence of the burley tobacco crop. At the polls, <ORGANIZATION> Eighty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eight </ORGANIZATION> belied its mostly Democratic registration and helped elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> president. It also sided with voters statewide in approving a constitutional amendment to allow a lottery, although <LOCATION> Barren </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> as a whole voted it down. Deep in July, <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, accustomed to gambles throughout a lifetime of farming, had to take another. As a crippling drought dragged on and his cattle ate the hay he had planned to feed them in October, Young had to decide whether to follow some of his neighbors and dump his 57 head of dairy and beef cattle on the market. `` I was beginning to think about it,'' said <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, 51, `` but I did n't.'' The gamble paid off. The rains returned by the end of July, early enough to coax another crop of hay from the ground and to get his burley _ a dry-weather crop, anyway _ off to a good start. `` This year the tobacco crop has turned out a whole lot better,'' said <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, who was in a decidely celebratory mood when he helped park cars at the 88 Celebration. `` I thought it was nice. We got a whole lot of recognition,'' he said. `` It wo n't happen for another 100 years. I do n't think I'll be parking cars at that one.'' Forty years ago, voters in Eighty Eight were chronicled by <PERSON> Ripley </PERSON>'s Believe It Or Not when they split in the presidential election _ 88 votes for President <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>, 88 votes for Republican <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON>. This year, the Eighty Eight precinct cast 88 votes for <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Freas </PERSON>, a Democrat from neighboring <LOCATION> Simpson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, in a race for an open state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat. Democrats hold a 3-2 registration edge, but Republican <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Barren </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> seat, got 231 votes here and won the election district-wide. Nor was <PERSON> Dickerson </PERSON> daunted by the Democrats' numbers as he lobbied locally for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> ticket of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, which got 216 votes to 147 for the Democratic ticket of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. `` It's still a rural precinct and the best way to campaign for any candidate is just word of mouth,'' <PERSON> Dickerson </PERSON> said. `` You have to do a selling job. It was particularly easy this year.''
</TEXT>
