<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Best and Worst in Film, Music and Theater</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 It was the year of a colossal flop and a colossal triumph on Broadway, of strikes and turmoil in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, of a pop-music bullseye in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION>. Here are the best and worst in film, theater and pop music in 1988, as compiled by <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, film critic and <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> reporter for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuchwara </PERSON>, AP drama writer, and the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s music critics:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MOVIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Best: _ ` `` Drunks are n't funny anymore. _ `` Full Moon in Blue Water.'' A regional-theater play-in-progress. _ `` The Lair of the White Worm.'' The pits from <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>. _ `` The Seventh Sign.'' `` The Exorcist'' without brains.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THEATER</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Best: _ `` The Phantom of the Opera.'' The year's biggest hit and its best musical. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Webber </PERSON> produced his most accomplished score to date _ lush, romantic and sweeping music that perfectly captured <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Leroux </PERSON>'s passionate tale of love denied. _ `` M. Butterfly.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hwang </PERSON>'s brilliant recreation of a spy scandal and love affair involving a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> diplomat and a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> opera singer who turns out to be a man. _ `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s Come and Gone.'' August <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s story of the search for identity among the children of slaves. _ `` The Road to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Athol </PERSON> <PERSON> Fugard </PERSON>'s tale of one woman's determination to remain independent _ `` Speed-the-Plow.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON>'s scathing look at <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> greed and glory. _ `` The Cocktail Hour.'' A.R. <PERSON> Gurney </PERSON>'s comic examination of upper-class generational conflict. Worst: _ `` <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON>.'' An $ 8 million disaster, Broadway's most expensive flop. It was based on the <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> horror novel about a dumpy, awkward teen-age girl with telekinetic powers. <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> and 16-year-old <PERSON> Linzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON>, in the title role, sang their hearts out, but nothing could save this dud. _ `` Chess.'' Another turkey that signaled that the British musical domination of Broadway was over. Despite its good score by <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> and members of <ORGANIZATION> ABBA </ORGANIZATION>, it died because of a deadly book by <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> and turgid direction by <P