</TEXT>
<HEAD>POP MUSIC</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Best: _ `` Rattle and Hum,'' U2. An ambitious, important and satisfying record. The Irish superstars swing wildly at numerous musical styles, and more often than not hit the mark in their part-live, part-studio double album. _ `` <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>. Stirring songs of love and social conscience from the year's most distinctive new voice. Sets one to wondering if <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> is An Important Artist For The 1990s or a folkie with a few great songs who just got a break. Her big tour did n't answer the question; her next album will. _ `` The <PERSON> Mona </PERSON> <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s Sister,'' <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>. A fine comeback by a brilliant artist all but given up for dead. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, one of the'70s finest songwriters, is caustic, as ever, but this literate and listenable record shows more facets of the man than anything he's done in years _ `` Talk Is Cheap,'' <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>. No, <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> ca n't sing But this is rousing, rocking, flat-out fun _ a raunchy, whiskey-soaked collection of songs with not a single frill attached. The only problem with `` Talk Is Cheap'' is that its release has revived childish arguments over who's the coolest, <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> or <PERSON> Keith </PERSON>. Well, we've always known it's <PERSON> Keith </PERSON>, have n't we? _ `` Conscious Party,'' <PERSON> Ziggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Marley </PERSON>. The son of reggae legend <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Marley </PERSON> delivers a sparkling debut. <PERSON> Ziggy </PERSON> appears to have his late father's knack for sharp, topical songs that also are danceable. Worst: _ `` Baby I Love Your Way-Free Bird Medley,'' Will To Power. All the worst memories of the'70s come rushing back, sort of like a bad meal. _ `` Do n't You Know What the Night Can Do,'