<HEAD>Meager Year for Musicals; Several New Plays Flourished</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was a meager year for musicals, but a half-dozen deserving new plays and several old ones managed to make it to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and flourish during 1988. `` The Phantom of the Opera'' was the year's biggest hit and its best musical. Deservedly so. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Webber </PERSON> produced his most accomplished score to date _ lush, romantic and sweeping music that perfectly captured <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Leroux </PERSON>'s passionate tale of love denied. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> was a heart-stopping and heart-breaking phantom, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Prince </PERSON>'s direction was impeccable, and <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Bjornson </PERSON> provided some eye-popping costumes and scenery. But after `` Phantom,'' which opened in January, nothing else excited the musical theater for the rest of the year. There were minor American musicals like the short-lived `` Mail'' and the two one-act musicals about love operating under the title `` Romance Romance.'' The inevitable turkeys also took to the stage, particularly two British gobblers, `` Carrie'' and `` Chess.'' `` Carrie,'' in particular, signaled that the British musical domination of Broadway was over. The show was an $ 8 million disaster, Broadway's most expensive flop. It was based on the <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> horror novel about a dumpy, awkward teen-age girl with telekinetic powers. <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> and 16-year-old <PERSON> Linzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hateley </PERSON>, in the title role, sang their hearts out, but nothing could save this dud. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> had better luck with plays, particularly new works by American authors. Topping the list, and also taking the Tony award as best play, was `` M. Butterfly,'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hwang </PERSON>'s brilliant recreation of a spy scandal and love affair involving a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> diplomat and a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> opera singer who turns out to be a man. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukes </PERSON> now plays the diplomat and gives such a compelling, on-the-edge performance that the play seems even better than when it first opened last March. Other notable new works by established playwrights included `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s Come and Gone,'' August <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s story of the search for identity among the children of slaves; <PERSON> Athol </PERSON> <PERSON> Fugard </PERSON>'s `` The Road to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>,'' a tale of one woman's determination to remain independent; `` Speed-the-Plow,'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON>'s scathing look at <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> greed and glory, and `` The Cocktail Hour,'' A.R. <PERSON> Gurney </PERSON>'s comic examination of upper-class generational conflict. Lesser-known playwrights also had success. Off-Broadway's `` Reckless,'' by <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, was a biting black comedy about a woman's escape from her family after her husband announces he plans to have her killed on Christmas Eve <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON>'s `` Eastern Standard'' offered another fascinating evening. It opens on Broadway Jan. 5, direct from off-Broadway's <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. The play follows several yuppies as they try to grow up in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> during the late 1980s. It's a witty, compassionate play about the most disliked group in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Several actors gave memorable performances this year. Among the best: B.D. <PERSON> Wong </PERSON>, whose gender switch in `` M. Butterfly'' was nothing less than astonishing; <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, the distraught wife in `` Reckless''; <PERSON> Yvonne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryceland </PERSON>, the feisty, independent sculptor in `` The Road to Mecca''; <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Silver </PERSON>, oozing an insincere charm as a smarmy would-be <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> producer in `` Speed-the-Plow,'' and <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchand </PERSON> as a diplomatic and wise WASP matriarch in `` The Cocktail Hour.'' But there were other performances that some actors might want to erase from their Playbill biographies: <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Pacino </PERSON>, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON> massacring `` <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Caesar </PERSON>'' in more ways than one; <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON>, sleepwalking through her role in `` Speed-the-Plow''; and <PERSON> Mariette </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartley </PERSON> coming to grief as a grief-stricken queen in <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s rarely produced `` King <PERSON> John </PERSON>.'' Most underrated performance: <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Brightman </PERSON> in `` The Phantom of the Opera.'' Sure she is n't <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernhardt </PERSON>, but the woman has a glorious, pristine voice that would be terrific to hear in some classic musical comedy by <PERSON> Rodgers </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gershwin </PERSON> or <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>. And <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Webber </PERSON> wrote the role of <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> in `` Phantom'' for her. If there's any doubt, listen to the singers who have followed her in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> cast. Not even close. Most overrated performances: Four of the five performers in the revival of `` Ai n't Misbehavin'.'' The show should have been called `` Are Misbehavin',' considering the extra histrionics _ vocal and otherwise _ by <PERSON> Nell </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON>, <PERSON> Armelia </PERSON> <PERSON> McQueen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charlaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodard </PERSON>. Only <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Shields </PERSON> managed to rein in the theatrics. The year produced three exceptional revivals: <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Brook </PERSON>'s spare but satisfying version of <PERSON> Chekhov </PERSON>'s `` The Cherry Orchard,'' done by the <ORGANIZATION> Brooklyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>'s Majestic Theater; <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Casey </PERSON>'s `` Juno and the Paycock,'' in an atmospheric production from the Gate Theater in <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION>; and the <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION>'s dark, brooding version of <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s `` Our Town. Not hitting the mark was the year's most anticipated revival, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON>'s `` Waiting for Godot,'' starring <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and directed by <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. The ticket demand was enormous. Most people, including some subscribers to the Lincoln Center Theater, could n't get in, but what they missed was more post-modern burlesque than <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON>.
