<HEAD>Paralyzing Strike and Furor over `Last Temptation'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Furor over a film about <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>, corporate turmoil and a paralyzing strike troubled the movie world in 1988. But it was a year of record prosperity and cautious optimism about the future. Major attractions in the holiday market guarantee that film grosses will pass last year's record of $ 4.85 billion. After a roaring summer and a slight dip after Labor Day, ticket sales boomed over the Thanksgiving weekend with such movies as `` Scrooged,'' `` <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> and Company'' and `` The Land Before Time.'' Two comedies, `` The Naked Gun'' and `` Twins,'' the drama `` Rain Man'' and other December offerings will help swell the year's total, demonstrating anew that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has an almost insatiable appetite for movie entertainment. But not everything in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> was coming up roses. Several film companies that expanded their output when movies started booming five years ago have now run into trouble. <ORGANIZATION> DeLaurentiis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> and the Cannon Group suffered heavy losses and were struggling to survive. After venturing disastrously into feature films, <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telepictures </ORGANIZATION> hit the skids and merged into <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION>. Two of the greatest names of film history, the merged <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION>, underwent a turbulent year, losing its production heads Producers <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Guber </PERSON> tried to buy a portion of the company, as did the <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Both deals collapsed. By year's end, the fate of <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION> was still in limbo The merger of <ORGANIZATION> Tri-Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> into a single entity, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>, was also in an unsettled state. The company suffered a $ 104 million loss earlier this year, mostly in movie write-downs _ losses from movies that are not released on schedule. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 49 percent of the new company, was rumored to be seeking an exit from the movie business. `` The Last Temptation of Christ,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>'s film about what might have happened if <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> had survived the cross, caused an uproar that is still being played out around the world. Religious fundamentalists staged a huge rally at <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>, urging the company to withdraw the film on grounds that it was sacrilege because the movie features a dream sequence in which <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> makes love to <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Magdelene </PERSON>. Universal remained firm, and `` The Last Temptation'' did fair business, hampered by the refusal of some theater chains to book it. The controversy continues as the film moves abroad. <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> is the latest country to ban it. Having barely avoided a directors' strike last year, <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> producers were struck by the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in 1988. The strike lasted 22 weeks and ended with a virtual standoff. Feature production did not seem slowed by the walkout, but the opening of the 1988-89 television season was postponed. The colorizing of black-and-white vintage movies continued to rile movie buffs as well as the <ORGANIZATION> Directors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and its members, but they could do nothing to stop the televising of tinted versions of `` Casablanca,'' `` Boom Town'' and other classics. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, who owns the biggest supply of old movies, even threatened to colorize <LOCATION> Orson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Welles </LOCATION>' 1941 classic, `` Citizen Kane.'' `` The Last Emperor'' was the big winner at the Academy Awards, picking up Oscars for best picture and for <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertolucci </PERSON>'s direction, but for none of the actors The performance awards went to <PERSON> Cher </PERSON> -LRB- `` Moonstruck'' -RRB-, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> -LRB- `` Wall Street'' -RRB-, <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Connery </PERSON> -LRB- `` The Untouchables'' -RRB- and <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> -LRB- `` Moonstruck'' -RRB-. The once-ailing <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> proved to be the year's success story. With such attractions as `` Three Men and a Baby,'' `` Good Morning, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'' and `` Who Framed <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabbit </PERSON>,'' Disney deposed Paramount as the top-grossing studio, capturing 20 percent of the market. At year's end, <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> announced formation of <ORGANIZATION> Hollywood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> _ the studio's third movie production company _ to beef up its output of feature films. The new company is scheduled to start up Feb. 1 and to be making 12 movies a year within three years. The new division was conceived as the most efficient way to produce more movies to fill a void left by the failure of some competitors and cuts at others. Not only did Hollywood find comfort in theater business, but the cassette market also continued to boom, as evidenced by the long-awaited release of `` E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial.'' <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION>'s first shipment was a record 10.6 million units. That was more than twice as many as the previous record holder, <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Cinderella.''
