<HEAD>How Was Shroud Made? Where Are Whales Now? Who Were Those
Terrorists?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL CORMIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What finally became of <PERSON> Putu </PERSON> and Siku, those celebrated whales? What is the truth about the Shroud of <LOCATION> Turin </LOCATION>? Who bombed <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s motorcade? As 1988 draws to a close, some nagging questions remain unanswered:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE WHALES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 On Oct. 7, a hunter off <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barrow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, discovered three <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> gray whales trapped by early Arctic ice. In an expensive international operation, <ORGANIZATION> Eskimos </ORGANIZATION> cut breathing holes for the whales with chain saws, and two Soviet icebreakers cleared a channel for the whales to start their trip back to open water. One of the whales apparently died in the process. The weary survivors, dubbed Siku -LRB- Ice -RRB- and <PERSON> Putu </PERSON> -LRB- Ice Hole -RRB-, faced a swim to the open sea of 200 ice-clogged miles, to join 21,000 fellow grays migrating 5,000 miles to warmer waters off <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The whales have n't been seen again and are unlikely to be spotted, but hope is high for their survival. `` They had the will to live,'' says rescue coordinator <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>. `` They should make it.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE SHROUD OF TURIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Science heightened the mystery surrounding the Shroud of <LOCATION> Turin </LOCATION> Oct. 13 when the Roman Catholic archbishop of <LOCATION> Turin </LOCATION> announced that, according to lab tests, the cloth is no more than 728 years old and can not be the burial cloth of Christ. The linen strip, 14 feet, 3 inches long and 3 feet, 7 inches wide, bears the faded image of a scourged and crucified man. Scientists say they have determined the shroud was not the product of an artist, but do not know how the haunting image was made. Those who believed it was Christ's burial cloth had attributed the image to a sudden blaze of light, fitting Biblical accounts of the resurrection. Others suspect radiation, or an unexplained chemical reaction between body secretions and the cloth. The bishop, <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Balestrero </PERSON>, says carbon-14 tests on tiny samples date the cloth to between 1260 and 1390. Although critics are now quick to brand the linen a medieval fake, the church says the cloth continues to be a venerated symbol of faith, and the mystery of its origin remains.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE SHULTZ ATTACK</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> escaped unharmed Aug. 8 when a bomb exploded near his motorcade as he traveled to downtown <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, from a nearby airport. The blast tore up pavement, damaged three cars and blew out the car window next to <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s wife. No one was hurt. <LOCATION> Bolivian </LOCATION> investigators said they believe a radical leftist group, the <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bolivar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commando </ORGANIZATION>, was involved. Little is known about the group, which claimed responsibility for targeting <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> during his 10-day Latin American tour. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> was investigating the attack but said it would not release its findings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE CRUISE SHIP ATTACK</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 On July 11, terrorists fired guns and hurled grenades aboard the Greek cruise ship City of <LOCATION> Poros </LOCATION>, killing nine people and injuring 98 other passengers returning from a day-long cruise on the <LOCATION> Aegean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> concluded that the Abu Nidal Palestinian group probably mounted the attack, but the organization denied responsibility. Anonymous callers claimed responsibility for a variety of other groups. One theory was that the terrorists may have been seeking freedom for <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON>, a Palestinian jailed in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> for entry on a forged Syrian passport. <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON> is wanted by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on charges he planted a bomb on a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet in 1982 that killed one person and injured 15.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE KUWAIT HIJACKING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Kuwaiti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet with 112 passengers and crew was hijacked April 5 on a flight from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and rerouted to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. Two Kuwaitis were killed before the last hostages were freed in <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> as the 16-day ordeal reached a negotiated end. Western intelligence sources said the nine hijackers were believed to be pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems of the Lebanon-based <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God. But the identities of the hijackers were never revealed. One published report said the hijackers were flown from <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and later reached <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> by land. There was no independent confirmation, but one diplomat, insisting on anonymity, said, `` The men are believed to have gone underground with <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> in a largely Shiite part of west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> where their trail is easily lost.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE ZIA CRASH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A Pakistani military plane crashed just after takeoff Aug. 17 near <LOCATION> Bahawalpur </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, killing President <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphel </PERSON> and 28 others. A Pakistani report shed little light on who may have been responsible for what investigators concluded was probably an act of sabotage. The report ruled out accidental technical failure aboard the sturdy C-130 transport, and said investigators found no evidence of an anti-aircraft missile or a powerful bomb. But investigators discovered residues of chemicals that could be used in an explosive strong enough to cause a technical malfunction. If it was sabotage, suspects included agents of Soviet-allied <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, angered by <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s support for Afghan rebels; Pakistani ethnic or religious minorities; or agents of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, which has fought three wars with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> have denied any involvement. Some published reports suggested that if the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> is implicated, neither <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> nor <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> will want to make such charges public, in order to avoid a confrontation.
</TEXT>
