<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales in November got the crucial holiday shopping season off to a fast start by posting a second consecutive strong monthly gain, the government said. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that sales jumped 1.1 percent in November to a seasonally adjusted $ 138.1 billion. That followed a 1.6 percent increase in October, revised upward from an earlier estimate of 0.9 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The deficit in the broadest measure of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade shrank to $ 30.89 billion from July through September, the smallest imbalance in three years, the government reported. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that the nation's deficit in its current account narrowed by 8.4 percent after an 8.6 percent drop in the second quarter Half the improvement in the third quarter came from a decline in the merchandise trade deficit, which dropped to $ 28.5 billion, reflecting a record level of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy is likely to do better in 1989 than it has this year, because of growth in exports and capital spending, the nation's purchasing managers said. Fifty-three percent of the purchasing managers surveyed felt their businesses would be better in 1989 than in 1988, compared with 13 percent who expected it would be worse, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Purchasing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The rest thought it would be about the same. The report is based on a survey of purchasing executives in more than 250 industrial companies in all 50 states.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumers became more cautious about their economic futures in November following the presidential election and the renewed debate over the budget deficit, a business-financed research group reported. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday its Consumer Confidence Index declined to 113.1 in November from a revised 116.9 in October. The monthly survey, which covers 5,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> households, indicated that although consumers showed more confidence in present employment conditions last month than in October, they turned less confident about the outlook for the next six months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of insolvent savings institutions declined for the third consecutive quarter in the July-September period, but even as government rescues soared other institutions were slipping under water, regulators said. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates federally insured thrift associations, said Tuesday that 434 of 3,024 such institutions were insolvent at the end of September, down from 498 three months earlier and substantially lower than the peak of 520 at the end of last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> auditors will expand a review of top military contractors that already has found <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxpayers are being billed for millions of dollars in questionable consulting fees, officials said. The first investigation covered a dozen contractors, but the new review will look at 18 more over the next 10 weeks, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contract </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. The review was ordered by <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> in the wake of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s ongoing investigation of possible fraud and bribery involving defense contractors.
