<SECOND>PM-Holiday Travel, Bjt,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>More People Traveling By Bus, Train, Plane This Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOROTHY GAST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If projections by the nation's train, air and bus lines are any indication, more Americans than ever will be traveling during the Christmas and New Year's holidays in 1988. Greyhound, the nation's largest intercity bus line, says it will carry 1.34 million passengers between Dec. 18 and Jan. 3, or 10 percent more than the 1.2 million people transported during the holidays last year. In part, the bus line attributes the increase to a recent boost in air fares and the limited availability of discount-priced seats on the nation's major airlines, said Greyhound Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Currey </PERSON>, who was in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> on Tuesday to meet with company employees. `` Airplane ticket prices are very substantially higher this year, and they are a factor,'' <PERSON> Currey </PERSON> told reporters. `` And bus fares are very moderately priced.'' <PERSON> Currey </PERSON>'s contention was disputed by organizations representing airlines and the nation's travel agents. `` Most people buying at Christmas bought their tickets weeks and months ago before fares went up,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidoff </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Belair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bowie </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, president-elect of the travel agents' group. `` What's going to happen next year, I do n't know. If the increases are put into effect for January, it probably will mean more people will take buses than ever before.'' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents the nation's largest airlines, said a record 7 million Americans traveled by air during the Thanksgiving holiday weekend. Between Dec. 17 and Jan. 2, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines expect to transport at least 22 million people, or about 500,000 more than for the same period last year, he said. That would also be a record, <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> said. The nation's major airlines announced last month that they were boosting most of their lowest discount fares and eliminating the cheap fares that can be booked a few days before a flight. But a week later, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> airlines announced reductions in some of their fares. `` Those fare increases that were announced just prior to Thanksgiving affected a very small percentage of the travel market,'' <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, public relations manager for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Passenger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, better known as <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION>, said the railroad carried a record number of passengers in the fiscal year that ended Sept. 30 and `` it shows no signs of letting up.'' But limited capacity makes it difficult for the railroad to set holiday records, he said. `` During the holiday seasons, they tend to sell out, making it impossible to improve from year to year and from one holiday season to the next,'' <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Denny </PERSON> <PERSON> Yatteau </PERSON>, Greyhound regional manager in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, said he expects 38,300 Greyhound tickets to be sold in the state for the Christmas-New Year's season. That would be an increase of 12 percent over a year ago. <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said space is limited on most <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> trains traveling from <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> this holiday season. <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> trains traveling from <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> on Dec. 23 already are sold out, he said.
