<HEAD>Massive Expansion Marks Start of Eastern Ski Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inspired by better snowmaking technology and growing attendance, ski resorts in the Northeast are spending millions of dollars in what industry officials call the region's greatest expansion since the 1960s The smaller, forested slopes of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> also have embarked on a marketing campaign designed to persuade skiers that skiing here is just as good as in the wide-open slopes of the <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>. `` The weather's been good and snow conditions have been favorable,'' said <PERSON> Cal </PERSON> <PERSON> Conniff </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ski </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Areas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. `` As a result, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> ski-area operators have been plowing quite a bit of money into new equipment.'' In the country's largest skiing development project this year, <LOCATION> Waterville </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> is spending $ 30 million to make the resort set 10 miles inside a national forest the `` Aspen of the East.'' <LOCATION> Waterville </LOCATION> is adding restaurants, boutiques, tennis courts and a high-speed detachable chair lift that cuts the trip to the top of the mountain in half. It has 30 new acres of slopes and snowmaking equipment to cover 96 percent of the trails. `` It's really an economic window of opportunity,'' said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiedaisch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Waterville </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>'s vice president. `` We've always had a pent-up market but we wanted more capacity. We were often maxed out in our capacity.'' In other recent developments: _ <LOCATION> Stratton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> spent $ 4.5 million to install the largest ski lift in the country, a 12-passenger gondola able to carry 2,400 people an hour _ <LOCATION> Burke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Burke </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, is making more than $ 1 million in improvements to the 25-year-old ski area, including construction of 100 condominiums and a 20 percent expansion of snowmaking capabilities _ <LOCATION> Shawnee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peak </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Bridgton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, is spending about $ 1.2 million to stimulate a money-losing operation by adding new lifts, rental equipment, more lodge space and lights that will make it the largest night skiing resort in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> _ After a $ 1.5 million overhaul, Ski Adventure in <LOCATION> Ashby </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, is expected to reopen in December, six years after the old <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Watatic </LOCATION> ski area went bankrupt and closed The 185 ski areas in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> led the nation in expansion this year, spending $ 60.9 million on improvements, compared with $ 56 million spent by <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> resorts and $ 51 million in <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> ski areas, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ski </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Areas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. In 1987, Northeast ski areas spent $ 92.1 million, 2 -LCB- times the 1985 level. Last year, the eight states in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> reported about 15 million skier visits, compared with 17 million in the <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>. In the 1984-85 season, attendance was less than 12 million in the East. The East has a basic topographic disadvantage because its tallest mountains are less than half the size of the 10,000 - to 12,000-foot peaks found in the <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> is the region's tallest mountain at 6,200 feet. The <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION> also offer complete resort areas with open skiing in wide, snowy fields. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, most trails are cut through woods and ski areas are typically limited to lodges and have few other recreational opportunities. To meet the competition, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> skiing associations have expanded on a national campaign _ `` Let's Go Skiing America'' _ by pushing for vacations at local resorts and trying to broaden modest increases in attendance over the last two years. `` It's not because they're losing market share to the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> or some non-ski service,'' said <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Camp </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ski </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Areas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, an industry group. `` The rate of growth of the consumer market in skiing has not been rapid like it was 15 or 18 years ago.'' In <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, ski areas are teaming up to make the state's resorts a destination. One new program allows interchangable lift tickets at Smugglers, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Peak </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Sugarbush </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ski </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Areas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> this year also began coordinating fly-drive packages from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> to build on the state's traditional bases of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. More man-made snow is being poured on slopes earlier than ever. A 2-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> product called Snomax allows snow to be made at temperatures 4 degrees to 8 degrees warmer than before, as high as freezing. Thanks to more sophisticated snowmaking, <ORGANIZATION> Camp </ORGANIZATION> said more than 50 of the 72 public ski areas in the six-state <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> region were open last weekend, a `` quantum leap'' over previous years. Said <PERSON> Conniff </PERSON>: `` The technology that's come along has taken a lot of the risk out of the business in the last three or four years.'' The onset of cold weather also has encouraged area ski officials hopeful that single-digit temperatures will persuade city dwellers to head for the slopes. `` The most important thing this cold weather has given us is an unprecedented jump on snowmaking efforts,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemel </PERSON>, general manager of the Powder Ridge Ski Resort in <LOCATION> Middlefield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> `` More slopes are opening faster than I've ever seen in the seven years I've been here.''
