<HEAD>Icahn Boosts Stake in Texaco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is facing renewed pressure from financier <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, who has raised his stake in the third-biggest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil company and has n't discouraged speculation he might resurrect a failed takeover bid. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> stoked the smoldering takeover speculation about <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday, disclosing he had increased his stock ownership to 15.8 percent of the company's 240 million shares outstanding. Securities analysts said <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s move, which helped boost <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price, evidently reflected his impatience at the pace of the company's post-bankruptcy restructuring aimed at increasing the value of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> stock. Some said <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s largest shareholder, probably had no interest in acquiring the company himself but might be attempting to induce another investor to make an offer. `` I think ultimately he's looking for a way to cash in,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaspar </PERSON>, who follows <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> for the Milwaukee-based investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> W. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baird </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` I think he's trying to stir up the pond and attract some outside interest to take a look at <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>.'' Others did not rule out the possibility of a takeover attempt by <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, who began acquiring <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> stock while the company was under federal bankruptcy court protection a year ago. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> declined to comment on why he raised his stake. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> officials also declined to comment. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> stock rose 87 -LCB- cents a share Tuesday to $ 51.62 -LCB- in heavy trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, an indication that investors believe either <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> or someone else may try to win control of the company. Last spring, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> made an offer for <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> valued at $ 14.5 billion, or $ 60 a share, as part of a shareholder proxy fight to oust the company's board. But his strategy was defeated by shareholders loyal to the board, which promised to boost <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price through an aggressive restructuring But since then, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> stock has not risen significantly, raising the possibility that more shareholders would align themselves with <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> if he undertook another takeover attempt. Moreover, some analysts said, the idea that <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> could raise the financing for such a takeover is not far-fetched. `` Last spring, nobody believed anybody could raise $ 14 or $ 15 billion for an acquisition,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aydin </PERSON>, an oil securities analyst at the Cleveland-based investment firm <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` This year it's different.'' The most notable example is the record $ 24.53 billion acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> by the buyout firm <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced less than two weeks ago. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> said in a filing with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that he purchased 2.6 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> between Dec. 7 and Dec. 12 for about $ 131 million, or an average of $ 50.37 -LCB- a share. Some <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> analysts and takeover attorneys thought <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s move signaled he was not interested in buying the company, because it vaulted his stake over a 15 percent threshold that under some circumstances triggers the anti-takeover laws of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> is incorporated. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> would have to immediately raise his ownership to 85 percent or wait at least three years before attempting any hostile acquisition that would result in the company's breakup, attorneys familiar with the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> law said. His latest move came against a background of resurgent rumors that he was growing exasperated with <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s multibillion dollar asset-shedding program and the company's failure to specify the date of a promised $ 1.7 billion distribution to shareholders. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> is chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, one of his successful acquisitions. He widely is regarded as a shrewd financier and takeover investor and has gone after some of the biggest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations, such as <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Phillips </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. He has been a thorn in the side of <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> management, which has been preoccupied with restructuring the company since it emerged from bankruptcy protection several months ago after settling a multibillion dollar dispute with <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>.
