<SECOND>PM-IBM-Rolm, Bjt,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Announces Rolm Sale-Venture With Germany's Siemens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is reducing its role in the telecommunications equipment business by selling part of its money-losing <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION> operation to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> and putting the rest of <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION> into a joint venture with <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION>. The deal announced Tuesday marks another chapter in <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s mixed success with <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION>, a freewheeling <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> company that the computer giant bought four years ago for an estimated $ 1.5 billion to help it link computers through phone switches. <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION> is believed to have lost hundreds of millions of dollars in recent years, but has grown into the nation's biggest seller of office phone switches _ which route calls within buildings _ under <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s ownership. The purchase would make <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> the world's biggest seller of office phone switches. <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> could consolidate its lead if it manages to buy <ORGANIZATION> Italtel </ORGANIZATION>, an Italian phone company, and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, for which it is making a $ 3.1 billion hostile offer in cooperation with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION> The price <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> is paying was not disclosed, but <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> said the deal would have no material effect on its income statement when it is completed early next year. That was taken as positive news for <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, because there had been speculation the sale price would be so low that <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> would be forced to take a large writeoff. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Akers </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive, said, `` I would absolutely not characterize it as a scaling back of <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s interests in telecommunications. He said the combination with <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> would allow <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> to offer a wider range of products to its customers than before. But analysts said <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> is turning over all responsibility for development and manufacture of Rolm-branded products to <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> and is discontinuing work on a complex office switch for the European market. `` For <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, it's a very clean market exit,'' said <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> McInerney </PERSON> of Northern Business Information-Datapro in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It is a graceful but not total retreat, no matter how you cut it,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbetta </PERSON>, a researcher for <ORGANIZATION> Probe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Knolls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> will sell the development and manufacturing arm of <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION>, with its 2,800 employees, to <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION>. It will become <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and include 700 employees now working for <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION> jointly will own a marketing and services company, known simply as <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION>, that will offer telecommunications products for private networks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It will have 5,500 employees who currently work for <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION> and fewer than 100 now working for <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> gradually will phase out a <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION> manufacturing and development plant in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, and offer jobs elsewhere in the company to the 550 affect employees. Those who do not accept transfers will be offered severance packages. Under <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s ownership, <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION> has lost money steadily, but its share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market has risen to 18.1 percent from 14.2 percent in 1984, according to Northern Business Information-Datapro. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> had bought <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION> as insurance in case the trend in computers was to connect them through office phone switches, according to <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosomworth </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn </LOCATION>. Instead, most office computers are connected through special local area networks, an area in which <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> is also strong. <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION> was vulnerable to competition because it does not make switches for the central offices of phone companies, in contrast to competitors such as <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANI