<HEAD>NTT Chairman Latest Victim of Japanese Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: NEW grafs 1-5 to UPDATE with Shinto's resignation; picks up
6th graf pvs bg'ng, The so-called ...; Combines pvs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the world's biggest company, resigned Wednesday under fire for alleged involvement in a scandal that has spread wide tentacles through <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s political and business world. The minister of posts and telecommunications, <PERSON> Masaaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakayama </PERSON>, told a news conference he had accepted the resignation of <PERSON> Hisashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinto </PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> chairman. <PERSON> Nakayama </PERSON> said Shinto had denied any personal involvement in dubious share trading but had accepted responsibility for actions by his personal secretary. Japanese press reports said prosecutors had traced some 10 million Japanese yen, or around $ 81,000, to Shinto's bank account from proceeds of the sale of shares in <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a real estate subsidiary of the Recruit conglomerate. Shinto on Tuesday had issued a statement denying involvement in the share transaction, which was carried out by his personal secretary, <PERSON> Kozo </PERSON> <PERSON> Murata </PERSON>, in 1986. <PERSON> Murata </PERSON> has since resigned as Shinto's aide. The so-called Recruit scandal last week brought the resignation of <PERSON> Kiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON> as finance minister and deputy prime minister, and has rocked the Japanese political and business worlds with allegations that the Recruit company was seeking favors by distributing shares in Recruit-Cosmos with a guarantee of easy, tax-free profits. <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION>, ranked as the largest corporation in the world in terms of stock market capitalization, had business links with Recruit, which bought two U.S.-made supercomputers from <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> and leased data communications circuits from the telephone giant. As a former telecommunications monopoly, <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> has been partially privatized, but Shinto and all other officials of the utility remain under regulations which make it illegal for them to receive cash or shares from private companies that <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> does business with. Shinto has been the chief executive of the telecommunications giant since 1981, when <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> was still a government-owned monopoly. He oversaw the privatization, which started in 1985, and then took the title of president. He held that post until last June, when he became chairman and chief executive, and the title of president went to <PERSON> Haruo </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamaguchi </PERSON>. Shinto's resignation would make him the most prominent victim in the business world of the Recruit scandal, which has also brought the resignation of news media executives and has broken several political careers in addition to that of <PERSON> Miyazawa </PERSON>, who a year ago was a major contender to be prime minister. Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> is on a list of prominent politicians whose aides profited from owning <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> shares, but he and the others denied any knowledge or involvement in the transactions. Among the others are former Prime Minister <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shintaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Abe </PERSON>, secretary-general of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The roots of the scandal go back to 1986 when unlisted <ORGANIZATION> Recruit-Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> shares were offered to the prominent figures or their aides, often to be paid for with loans from a Recruit-linked finance company. The shares were listed for sale in the over-the-counter market in October 1986 and immediately skyrocketed in value, yielding tax-free profits when they were sold.
