<HEAD>New Trans-Atlantic Cable Will Increase Phone Capacity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first fiber-optic telephone cable across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> goes into service Wednesday, greatly increasing the number of calls that can be placed to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> at one time, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, in Wednesday's editions, says the new cable can carry 40,000 calls simultaneously by using pulses of laser light to send voice and computer data. The three existing trans-Atlantic cables, made of copper, along with satellites, can carry a total of 20,000 calls, the Times noted. The new cable was installed over six months at a cost of $ 362 million and illustrates the increasing pace with which communications companies are stringing fiber-optic cables along the ocean floor and across <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. The cable is a joint venture of 29 European and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> telephone companies, including <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telcom </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T, which installed the cable, will also operate it.
