<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen today, while share prices rebounded on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid optimism about an impending <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade report, dealers said. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which dropped 74.48 points Tuesday, gained 156.92 points, or 0.53 percent, finishing at 29,754.73. The rebound followed the dollar's firming on the currency market as traders anticipated a narrowing of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit for October, said a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest brokerage. `` The dollar's uptrend encouraged stock investors to buy export-related issues such as <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Matsushita </PERSON>,'' said the dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said the same optimism first had pushed up the dollar on the currency market, prompting the Nikkei to rise. `` Investors are now expecting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit to shrink to about $ 9.5 billion,'' he added. September's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> deficit was $ 10.46 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> was to release the nation's trade figures for October later Wednesday. Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 1 billion shares. On the currency exchange market, the dollar closed unchanged from the opening at 123.35 yen, up 0.29 yen from Tuesday's close of 123.06 yen. The currency moved in a tight range of 123.25-123 .45 yen A <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> dealer said a majority of traders remained on the sidelines to await the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade report. `` The dollar-yen rate today was barely moving in a cautious mood,'' he said, adding that there was no other news to affect market trends. If the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit matches market expectations of about $ 10 billion, the dollar-yen rate is unlikely to change soon from the current level, he said.
