<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Lower At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices were lower in quiet trading at midday Wednesday amid nervousness ahead of the afternoon release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for October. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 9.1 points, or 0.5 percent, at 1,743.5 at about 12:30 p.m., just 0.4 point above its worst level of the morning. The index touched its best level, 3.2 points up, shortly after the opening. Shares opened on a positive note, as prices maintained the upward momentum seen Tuesday in what dealers called a technical rebound following the market's recent sharp falls. They were also boosted by news of a surprise drop in British industrial production which could indicate a slowing in demand and an easing of inflationary pressures. But sentiment was then hit by concerns that the recent hikes in British interest rates, and the strong pound, are hurting corporate profits. Traders also were nervous ahead of the 1:30 p.m. release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures. Volume was light, with 263.6 million shares changing hands by midday compared with 287.8 million shares at the same time Tuesday.
</TEXT>
