<HEAD>Report Says Drexel Facing Pressure to Accept Plea Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prosecutors are pressuring <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to accept a plea-bargain settlement that would include paying a $ 750 million fine and admitting guilt to at least five felony counts to avoid prosecution for racketeering and securities fraud, the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. Quoting sources it did not identify, the newspaper said both sides were close to an agreement late Tuesday that would end one of the most intensive criminal securities fraud investigations in history. A $ 750 million fine for securities fraud would dwarf the record $ 100 million in penalties paid two years ago by <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, the now-imprisoned stock speculator who turned state's evidence and has been a key source of evidence against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. The nation's fifth-largest securities firm has maintained innocence throughout an investigation that has been colored by press leaks and speculation. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> executives have said they are interested in a settlement to avoid prosecution and a lengthy trial, but admitting guilt would mark a stunning turnaround and open the firm to numerous civil lawsuits by investors who allege they were defrauded. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s chief spokesman, declined to comment on the Journal story. Officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office, who have been coordinating the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> investigation, also declined comment. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> is privately owned and is one of the most profitable Wall Street firms, specializing in the market for high-yield, high-risk debt securities commonly called `` junk bonds.'' It has played a major role in some of the biggest corporate takeovers of all time, including the record $ 24.53 billion acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced Nov. 30. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> is known to have set aside hundreds of millions of dollars for a potential settlement with the government. The firm is eager to avoid a racketeering indictment, which could seriously impair its business and involve enormous fines if a jury found <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> guilty. Three months ago <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filed a massive civil lawsuit that accused <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, its high-yield bond financier <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and three other key employees of conspiring with <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> to profit on inside information, manipulate stock, defraud <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> clients, keep phony books and other violations. A federal grand jury has been expected to indict <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> on criminal charges as well, but the indictments repeatedly have been delayed, evidently as a pressure tactic to convince the potential defendants to reach plea-bargain settlements instead. While <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> has expressed interest in settling, <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> has not negotiated with government prosecutors and has vowed to vindicate himself at trial.
</TEXT>
