<HEAD>State Airline Sacks 3,000 Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Nigeria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> has dismissed 3,000 workers, a third of the work force, in a bid to keep the bankrupt airline operating. Police surrounded the state airline's headquarters on Wednesday to prevent attacks. Earlier this year, the airline sharply reduced its overseas flights after accidents grounded some aircraft and two planes were seized for non-payment of debts. <ORGANIZATION> Nigeria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> has been denied overflight rights by some countries for refusing to pay its bills. The airline reportedly owes creditors more than $ 1 billion. International flight attendants were replaced with attendants from domestic flights this year after several attendants and flight crew members were arrested on drugs charges in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Some senior officials were among those dismissed Wednesday, including the director of engineering and maintenance. Retired Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Olu </PERSON> <PERSON> Bajowa </PERSON>, who was appointed administrator to resolve the airline's financial problems, announced the dismissals. In addition to management problems, the airline suffered through years of over-valuation of the Nigerian naira and its fares, set by the government, which often were below cost. Some officials of the military government have predicted the airline would be privatized. Last month, <PERSON> Bajowa </PERSON> ordered the airline to change the symbol on its planes' tail sections from a flying elephant to an eagle.
