<HEAD>Italian Pilots Call Three-Day Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Alitalia </ORGANIZATION> canceled 28 national and six international flights Wednesday due to a strike by pilots. The pilots decided to strike for two hours each morning on Wednesday, Thursday and Friday to protest the lack of progress in contract talks between union representatives and the state airline. The airline said 44 national and 10 international flights would be canceled Thursday. The number of cancellations for Friday was not immediately known. Negotiations between the pilots and the airline revolve around salary disputes. Air traffic controllers had called a strike for the same period, but Transportation Minister <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> <PERSON> Santuz </PERSON> ordered those workers to remain on the job.
