<HEAD>Dock Strike Paralyzes Brazilian Ports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of striking dock workers demanding higher pay have closed the nation's main ports, officials said today. Portobras, the government agency that operates the ports, said about 30,000 workers walked off their jobs Tuesday in 12 of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s 30 ports, including <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s biggest port The strike continued today, but there were few details of how widespread it was. About $ 3 million has been lost in uncollected port fees, the Portobras press office said. In <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>, 45 miles from <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>, the strike was causing daily losses of about $ 1.1 million, officials said. About 52,000 tons of products a day, ranging from automobiles and iron ore to soybeans and chemical products, `` are being left unhandled aboard 25 ships that are docked in Santos,'' said <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Sao </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paulo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, one of the directors of the <ORGANIZATION> Santos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said in a telephone interview that workers were demanding a 38 percent wage increase Neither he nor <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> would say what the average salary of a dock worker was. <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> said the dock company has not made any wage offers to the strikers `` because we barely have enough money to pay December's salaries. Inflation in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is running at more than 1,000 percent a year. On Nov. 23, workers at the nation's largest steel mill ended a 17-day strike marked by a clash with soldiers that left three strikers dead and scores injured. The workers, at the state-owned <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Volta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Redonda </LOCATION> northwest of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>, voted to accept a proposed wage increase.
