<FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 1111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-RetailView-Boutique Adv18   12-14 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Retail View-Boutique, Adv 18,0881</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Dec. 18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Small Store in the Big City Weathers Rough Economic Times</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Retail View-Lazarus</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ With the make-it or break-it season in full swing for the nation's retailers, The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> takes an inside look at how two stores are handling the holiday rush in side-by-side stories from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and Grand Rapids, <LOCATION> Mich </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Marcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Massa </PERSON> used to buy $ 280 sweaters to stock her small <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> boutique <PERSON> Osidi </PERSON>, but her expectations about holiday sales this year are slightly less ambitious. `` I'd shake if I took that in,'' said the store owner, explaining how the long slump in apparel sales has colored her inventory decisions for the season. While she did order a handful of $ 400 outfits _ with customers shopping for New Year's Eve in mind _ the shop's fashion statement this Christmas is stylish yet inexpensive. `` I think there's a big economic problem in the city,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Massa </PERSON> during a reporter's visit to <LOCATION> Osidi </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Gramercy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, south and to the east of midtown <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. But she also predicted, `` The season is going to be OK _ I have no doubt about that.'' When you think of shopping in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, big stores like <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION>'s or <ORGANIZATION> Bloomingdale </ORGANIZATION>'s come to mind, or on a smaller scale, the scores of trendy shops on Madison and <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> avenues <PERSON> Osidi </PERSON> is nothing like any of those retailers. It is a small neighborhood store that caters to women who live in what is a largely middle-class area. The bulk of Mrs. <PERSON> Massa </PERSON>'s business comes from regular customers _ many of whom she knows on a first-name basis and who do n't like the big stores. They periodically stop by just to see what's new and maybe chat and have a cup of coffee with the owner, an outgoing woman who obviously loves what she's doing. The store sells casual clothing and outfits that could be worn to work or to parties. Sweaters at <LOCATION> Osidi </LOCATION> go for $ 48 to $ 70, and two - and three-piece wool jersey outfits range from about $ 220 to the low $ 300s At this time of the year, there are a number of party dresses for about $ 200. <PERSON> Osidi </PERSON> does a lot of business in accessories: silver, antique and costume jewelry; scarves; lingerie; belts and pocketbooks. These `` low-ticket'' items have been the boutique's biggest sellers so far this season. Holiday sales at <LOCATION> Osidi </LOCATION> _ the store's name comes from the nickname of one of Mrs. <PERSON> Massa </PERSON>'s friends _ have been erratic this year. The Friday after Thanksgiving, in contrast to the mob scene uptown at <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bloomingdale </ORGANIZATION>'s and other big stores, <PERSON> Osidi </PERSON> was quiet, but Mrs. <PERSON> Massa </PERSON> was unperturbed. Although that day was the traditional start of the Christmas shopping season, it has never been a big day at her store. Business picked up over the following weekend, but sales have ebbed and flowed since then _ along with Mrs. <PERSON> Massa </PERSON>'s outlook. When volume picked up several days into December, she was pleased but realistic: `` It's nothing like it should be.'' Like most other stores across the country, <LOCATION> Osidi </LOCATION> has had to lower its expectations because of the nearly 2-year-old slump in retail spending. Mrs. <PERSON> Massa </PERSON>, who has been a clothing retailer or manufacturer for more than 20 years, said the 14 months since October 1987 have been the worst retail season she's seen. She remembers painfully well Oct. 19 of last year _ the day of the stock market crash. <PERSON> Osidi </PERSON> took in $ 30 in sales. Since then, her business has changed drastically. Some of <PERSON> Osidi </PERSON>'s customers _ who included stockbrokers _ lost their jobs Others became very wary _ `` they think twice,'' is the way Mrs. <PERSON> Massa </PERSON> puts it. `` That customer's not there any longer,'' she said of the women who used to spend freely. These days, she says, it is her regular customers who `` thank God keep me in business.'' She knows she's not alone, that other retailers have had the same troubles over the past year. And she's heard via the merchant grapevine that their Christmas season is going slowly. `` My suppliers say everyone's crying,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Massa </PERSON> went into the last two weeks of the season complaining that no one seemed to be in the Christmas spirit, yet she still expected things to turn out all right, if not great. `` Normally, we're a late store,'' she said, explaining that the bulk of her Christmas business comes in the final week, from last-minute shoppers and people who could n't find what they wanted anywhere else or who could n't contend with the uptown crowds. On the very last day of the season, Christmas Eve, she expects to see mostly men buying a lot of jewelry. Will she be satisfied at the end, if and when those eleventh-hour shoppers come through? No. `` The numbers just are n't there,'' she said, and added, `` No matter what you do, people are n't going to spend money.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Dec. 18</NOTE>
