<SECOND>BC-US-EEC,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Predicts U.S. Will Prevail On Agriculture Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will prevail in its fight with <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> over agricultural subsidies because its position is `` on the side of the angels,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said Wednesday. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, who is being considered for the post of Agriculture Secretary in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, also said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will retaliate against the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> if it implements a Jan. 1 ban on importing hormone-treated meat. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has already decided it will strike against some European imports, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, `` and that decision stands.'' He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has not found any evidence that hormone-treated animals endanger consumers' health, `` and therefore this is an illegal trade barrier.'' The ball is now in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s court `` and time is getting short,'' he said The 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> said last week it intends to implement the ban, which had already been put off for one year at the request of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The measure would affect some $ 170 million worth of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meat. One possible compromise offered by the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> would exempt meat which is used for pet food and which accounts for about 50 percent of the imports. <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> officials have said the Americans rejected that solution because they are determined to hold out for all or nothing as a matter of principle. Prospects for a compromise appeared to dim last week as relations between the two trading giants soured over an unrelated dispute about government support for farmers. The impasse blocked other progress at an international trade meeting of 100 nations in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> and left residues of bitterness on both sides of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. To avert collapse of the <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> meeting, which was a mid-term review of the four-year <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round of trade negotiations, participants agreed to meet again in the first week of April in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. `` Let's hope reason will prevail'' in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. If the agriculture issue is not solved, he warned, `` there's obviously jeopardy to the entire <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round.'' The controversy stems from a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demand that all members of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- abolish their farm supports which distort trade on the world market. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, under strong pressure from its large rural population, advocates reduction in subsidies but not elimination. `` We're on the side of the angels on this issue,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said, `` and everyone, including our <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies, knows this.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> contends that elimination of farm supports will lower government expenditure and ease the burden on consumers and taxpayers around the world. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> predicted political pressure on the Europeans would mount between now and April, `` and political pressure can generate political will'' to change positions. The pressure is expected to come from agricultural exporters such as <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, whose farmers are having trouble competing against the subsidized European and American farm exports.
