<HEAD>Australian Company to Buy Second Texas Specialty Retailer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In its second rescue of a troubled <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> retailer, an Australian property and retail company has signed a letter of intent to buy the <ORGANIZATION> Frost </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> chain for an undisclosed sum. <ORGANIZATION> Hooker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> bought 80 percent of the Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Sakowitz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in November 1987, bringing it out of bankruptcy <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakowitz </PERSON>, the chain's chairman and a member of its founding family, held the remaining 20 percent. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Hooker </PERSON> announced that L.J. <ORGANIZATION> Hooker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, its wholly owned subsidiary, would fold the San Antonio-based <ORGANIZATION> Frost </ORGANIZATION> chain into <PERSON> Sakowitz </PERSON>, operate all the stores under the <PERSON> Sakowitz </PERSON> name and put <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakowitz </PERSON> in charge of the combined operation. Both chains are high-priced merchandisers catering to wealthy customers and emphasizing upscale women's apparel. Both also operate four stores. All the <PERSON> Sakowitz </PERSON> outlets are in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, while Frost's are in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> In a prepared statement, Hooker Executive Chairman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Herscu </PERSON> said, `` The proposed expansion of <ORGANIZATION> Sakowitz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is a rare opportunity to bring together two of the finest names in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> specialty retailing targeted to the upscale and quality-conscious customer.'' Frost Bros. filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in April. The financially troubled retailer had gone public in an effort to improve its financial picture, but that plan fell through with the stock market crash of Oct. 19, 1987. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyly </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Torie </PERSON> <PERSON> Steele </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyly </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, had bought the chain from <ORGANIZATION> Manhatten </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for an estimated $ 50 million in August 1986, and <PERSON> Wyly </PERSON> said at the time he would concentrate on the `` Mercedes Benz niche'' in retailing. Between the purchase date and the bankruptcy filing, the number of stores was cut from 13 to nine. More stores were closed after filing, including two in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> _ at the <LOCATION> Galleria </LOCATION> and Memorial City shopping centers. Frost continues to operate its third <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> store near the exclusive <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION> neighborhood. The company had 1985 revenue of $ 120 million. More recent figures were not available. <PERSON> Hooker </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, is an aggressive buyer of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retailers and a real estate developer in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. It bought 80 percent of <PERSON> Sakowitz </PERSON> in 1987 for $ 7.5 million under an amended plan of reorganization filed in federal bankruptcy court. <PERSON> Sakowitz </PERSON> was the nation's last remaining high-fashion speciality retailer controlled by a founding family member. It filed for Chapter 11 reorganization protection in the wake of financial troubles stemming partly from the economic slump in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>. At the time of the filing in 1985, <PERSON> Sakowitz </PERSON> had 17 stores and six boutiques in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, a number of which since have been sold. Other <ORGANIZATION> Hooker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> holdings include <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the New York-based department store chain which it acquired in October 1987 for an undisclosed price, and <ORGANIZATION> Parisian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, specialty retailer which it acquired along with <ORGANIZATION> Parisian </ORGANIZATION>'s major shareholders in September 1987 in a $ 252 million buyout. <PERSON> Hooker </PERSON> also is developing four regional shopping malls in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, averaging 1.5 million square feet each.
