<FIRST>u f AM-OilReport     12-14 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Report,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petroleum Imports Continued To Rise In November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Petroleum imports rose sharply in November and domestic crude oil production took its biggest monthly dip this year, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday. Imports jumped 14.1 percent to an average 7.95 million barrels a day from 6.97 million barrels in November 1987, with imports of gasoline and other refined products reaching their highest level since 1974, according to <ORGANIZATION> API </ORGANIZATION>'s Monthly Statistical Report. Daily domestic crude oil production fell 4.3 percent _ the biggest decline this year _ to an average of 8.04 million barrels a day, due mainly to a slowdown in output in the lower 48 states. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> production remained steady at around 2 million barrels a day, the report said. Analysts said strong demand in November continued to consume the growing imports as total supplies of crude oil and refined products declined 3.6 percent compared with the same time last year. The institute said lower world crude prices helped boost imports for the first 11 months of 1988 to their highest level since 1980 as the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries continued its runaway production. However, <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members agreed last month to lower cartel production in the first six months of 1989. World crude prices have firmed slightly since the accord in anticipation of a cutback. In November, crude oil imports averaged 5.3 million barrels a day, up 7.8 percent from November 1987, the report said. Product imports rose 29 percent to an average 2.7 million barrels a day. Daily gasoline imports reached a new high of 630,000 barrels for the month, up 80,000 barrels a day from a year ago. Distillate and residual fuel oil imports also were strong. In the past three years, daily imports are up by 2.2 million barrels, with increasing demand accounting for about two-thirds of the increase and declining domestic production accounting for most of the remainder, the <ORGANIZATION> API </ORGANIZATION> said. But despite high imports, total inventories fell by 5 million barrels in November. API said inventories have fallen about 18 million barrels since July, or more than 50 million barrels after accounting for seasonal factors. Combined deliveries surged more than 1.3 million barrels a day, an 8.1 percent increase from the year-ago period. Gasoline deliveries rose 3.6 percent, or nearly 5 million barrels, even as motorists began cutting back on travel. Gasoline production rose 1.5 percent while gasoline stocks declined 6 million barrels from last November. Distillate deliveries rose 7.3 percent despite continued mild weather. Analysts said the rise probably reflected investors taking advantage of weak prices. The report also said utilization of the nation's refineries increased to 83.2 percent from 82.3 percent last November.
</TEXT>
