<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar retreated Wednesday, hurt by what money dealers called rumors of a hike in West German interest rates and a negative market reaction to the monthly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade report. Gold prices rose slightly in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading after easing marginally abroad. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> quoted bullion at $ 421 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $ 419.50 at the same time Tuesday. Foreign-exchange strategists said speculation that the West German central bank would tighten domestic credit conditions on Thursday raised demand for the West German mark and consequently increased the supply of dollars in the market, pushing down the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's value. Pressure on the dollar intensified after the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> merchandise trade deficit narrowed to $ 10.35 billion in October from $ 10.67 billion the month before. Although the shortfall was the smallest in three months, the market had anticipated an imbalance of about $ 10.5 billion. `` The figures came out in line with expectations, and since there's overriding bearish sentiment to the dollar, people just resumed selling it,'' said <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Yannalfo </PERSON>, a trader at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> commodities futures firm <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The only thing that could have prevented it would have been a really good number, like $ 7 or $ 8 billion.'' The monthly trade figures vary widely but have enormous potential to affect the dollar's value because they are considered one of the most visible indicators of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> competitiveness and economic strength. A widening deficit suggests exports are weakening and the dollar will fall, while a narrowing shortfall suggests exports are strengthening and the dollar will rise. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where markets closed before the trade report was released, the dollar rose 0.29 Japanese yen to 123.35 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar dropped to 122.60 yen. By the time trading ended in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar fetched 122.67 yen, down from 123.29 yen late Tuesday. The British pound rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 1.8335 from $ 1.8280 late Tuesday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> sterling fetched $ 1.8295, up from $ 1.8190 late Tuesday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with rates late Tuesday, included: 1.7374 West German marks, down from 1.7497; 1.4655 Swiss francs, down from 1.4717; 1.2020 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1999; 5.9390 French francs, down from 5.9790; and 1,285.25 Italian lire, down from 1,288.71. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with rates late Tuesday, included: 1.7365 marks, down from 1.7410; 1.4630 Swiss francs, down from 1.4705; 5.9350 French francs, down from 5.9775; 1.9590 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9715; 1,279.50 Italian lire, down from 1,286.50; and 1.1986 Canadian dollas, down from 1.1995. Gold prices moved in a narrow range. At the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose $ 1.70 a troy ounce to $ 421.50. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, gold fetched $ 420.75 an ounce, unchanged from late Tuesday; in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> gold fell 45 cents to $ 420, and in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> it fell 16 cents to $ 421.38. Silver bullion for current delivery rose 0.9 cent a troy ounce to $ 6.177 on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, silver fell 1 cent to $ 6.16 an ounce.
