million in sales was set in 1986. He said the 15.4 million estimate for the 1989 calendar year would be `` down from this year, but still a good industry.'' `` I'd be worried when our -LRB- market -RRB- share begins to run into problems,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market share for cars is 21.7 percent, he said. During the meeting, <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> also said: _ Buyer incentives would continue during the coming year, but `` I do n't see us leading the charge. He said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> would remain competitive when other automakers offer incentives. _ Discussions are under way for assembly of a car, probably modeled on <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s West German-made Scorpio, in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> The car probably would be made in an existing or new plant in the Gorky area. <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> also said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s North American earnings likely will be down from last year, resulting in smaller profit-sharing payments to <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> employees early in 1989. Earlier this week, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced profit-sharing payments of about $ 200 for each hourly and salaried worker, the first time since 1985 that the nation's No. 1 automaker has made such payments. `` I think it -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s profit-sharing payment -RRB- will be more than $ 200,'' <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> said, smiling. <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> said a proposal for a 15-cent-per-gallon gasoline tax increase should be considered by the incoming <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration only if other deficit reduction measures, especially federal spending cuts, prove unsuccessful. He said a 5-cent-a-year phase-in of such a tax increase would soften the blow on the auto industry, and provisions such as tax cr