<HEAD>Sales Slump In Early December</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks fell 11 percent in early December compared with a burst of incentive-driven sales in the same period a year ago, figures released Wednesday showed. The companies said they sold an average of 29,610 vehicles during each of the nine selling days in the Dec. 1-10 period this year, compared with an average of 33,251 during the same period last year, when there also were nine selling days. Car sales fell 10.5 percent and light truck sales dropped 11.7 percent in early December. Analysts said the declines were n't worrisome because of the revival of incentives during the period last year. `` They started putting on some heavy-duty incentives'' in early December last year, said analyst <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` You've got a tough time to compare it with. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Sudol </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Fitch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> agreed. `` That's hard to read,'' she said. `` It's not surprising that they're down a little bit, given that December is bad for auto sales anyway. `` In any -LRB- recent -RRB- 10-day period, you've had so much noise in the period that it's hard to make a comparison,'' <PERSON> Sudol </PERSON> added. `` That noise is incentives.'' Both agreed that despite the early December slip, the industry is healthy. As the calendar year draws to a close, the companies are looking forward to what could be the second-best sales year in history, behind the 16.3 million vehicles sold in 1986. For the year, sales by companies making cars and light trucks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have risen 6.9 percent in 1988 over 1987, going to a daily rate of 37,949 this year compared with a daily rate of 35,499 last year. Among the Big Three, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> showed the largest early-December decline in car sales, falling 12.9 percent to a daily rate of 8,906 cars in 1988 from 10,226 last year. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales were up 0.9 percent in 1988 over 1987 to a daily rate of 11,776 this year from 11,668 last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s sales in early December fell 11.6 percent to a daily rate of 5,582 this year compared with 6,316 in the same period last year. But for the year, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales have climbed 7.7 percent to an average daily rate of 7,121 in 1988 compared with 6,612 in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> said it sold cars at a daily rate of 2,673 in early December this year compared with 2,979 during the same period last year, a 10.3 percent decline. So far this year, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has sold 10.3 percent more cars, with a daily sales rate of 3,451 in 1988 compared with 3,130 last year.
