<HEAD>Tonnage Up, Market Share Holds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Steel imports rose 7.1 percent to 17.6 million tons for the first 10 months of 1988, but strong domestic demand held foreigners' share of the market near the goal of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> quota program, according to figures released Wednesday. Over 10 months of 1988, imports accounted for 20.4 percent of the market, practically the goal set by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration when it introduced import quotas in 1984. Imports in October declined to 1.5 million tons from 1.64 million tons in September and 1.61 million tons in October 1987. The figures, based on <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> data, were released in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. The rival <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Imported </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> said that after deducting 2.5 million tons of steel imports bought by domestic mills for further processing, 10-month imports totaled 15 million tons, or 17.5 percent of the market. The percentage figure is well below the 18.5 percent target set for finished steel products. `` With -LRB- quotas -RRB- expiring in nine months and much being heard for and against renewal, overriding factors in any decision in addition to interest of domestic steel producers must also be those of domestic steel users, fabricators and manufacturers of steel-intensive products whose very existence creates the market for both domestic steel producers and importers,'' said <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, president of the importers institute and vice chairman of the importing firm <ORGANIZATION> Steelinter </ORGANIZ