<HEAD>Mexico Wants Reduced Debt Payment Level</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is asking its creditors to reduce its annual foreign debt payments to the equivalent of 3 percent of its gross national product from the present 5 percent, according to <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON>. <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> told federal senators and deputies on Tuesday that the new administration of President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> had outlined the proposal to creditor banks in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> did not disclose details of the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> proposal, but the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> financial daily <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiero </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday said the proposal would nearly halve <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s anticipated $ 16 billion debt service bill in 1989. The <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> newspaper El Universal on Wednesday reported the proposal won a sympathetic response from European bankers but `` has encountered obstacles and resistance in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because of the change of government'' there. The newspaper said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bankers have adopted a wait-and-see attitude toward the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> proposal, at least until President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is inaugurated on Jan. 20. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, who was sworn in Dec. 1, repeatedly has warned that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> can not continue to devote 5 percent of its gross national product each year to service its $ 102 billion foreign debt, the developing world's second-highest after <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will pay an estimated $ 14 billion in interest and principal on the debt in 1988. <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Financiero </PERSON> said <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> told a meeting of labor leaders on Monday that <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' negotiating team wants a debt restructuring agreement that would target a greater proportion of Mexican payments toward debt principal. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> also wants creditor banks to acknowledge the real value of Mexican debt paper as determined by the secondary market and to reschedule <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s servicing payments accordingly, the newspaper said. The secondary market has valued <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s debt at 50 cents on the dollar. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> newspapers on Wednesday reported that <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> plans to visit <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in the next few days to take up the proposal with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s creditors. Creditor banks have balked this year on moves toward Mexican debt-reduction proposals. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> did reduce its debt principal by $ 1.1 billion through a U.S.-backed bond auction earlier this year, but the reduction was far less than officials originally hoped for. <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON>'s disclosure of the new reduction target came after <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> named former <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Gustavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Petricioli </PERSON> as the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, yet another sign of the president's eagerness to achieve rapid progress in restructuring negotiations
