<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it plans to crack down on stations that sell leaded gasoline at far cheaper prices and allow motorists to put it in no-lead cars. Lead disables pollution control equipment, causing increases of up to 80 percent in emissions of pollutants, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> says. The agency said it had written refiners and marketers warning that inspectors would pay close attention to stations where leaded gasoline is priced significantly below unleaded regular. There are no federal penalties against individual motorists who use the wrong fuel, but <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> may impose civil fines of up to $ 10,000 on stations that permit it. Some states, however, make it an offense for individuals too. `` There really is n't any excuse for pricing unleaded above leaded'' since leaded now costs more to make, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, head of the mobile sources division in <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s air pollution program. The agency has only 20 inspectors of its own, but hires an unspecified number through contractors. These inspectors for years have been checking station tanks and, in cooperation with local police deparments, making spot checks of cars on the road. Those checks consistently show that one car in five has used the wrong fuel or had its pollution control devices tampered with at some time. At present, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimates that 6 percent of cars requiring no-lead are using leaded gasoline, down from more than 10 percent a few years ago. Lead compounds have been added to gasoline since the 1920s because they are the cheapest antiknock additive, by far. Until the 1970s, car engines also relied on the compounds for valve seat lubrication. Some heavy duty engines did until the mid-1980s. Concern over pollution as well as lead toxicity led <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 to order maximum permissible lead reduced by more than 90 percent, from 1.1 gram per gallon to 0.1 gram. This means higher refining costs to produce a given octane. <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>'s Oilgram, a trade publication, on Monday reported wholesale prices for leaded up to 2 cents a gallon higher than regular unleaded except in the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> and farther west, where the two grades generally were the same. Energy Department figures show leaded gasoline sold retail at 4.7 cents per gallon cheaper than regular unleaded for the first nine months of 1988. Currently, leaded gasoline is 15 percent of the market compared with 21 percent a year ago. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Koach </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s threats to fine dealers $ 10,000 are assinine.'' <PERSON> Koach </PERSON> complained: `` It's difficult for dealers to control misfueling. We've had reports of dealers threatened with violence'' for trying to stop customers from buying leaded. Independent dealers, he said, are pressured to adhere to retail prices their suppliers decide on. `` Why is leaded gasoline still cheaper? It's the oil companies' policy,'' <PERSON> Koach </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Stow </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION>, a major national brand that has stopped all leaded sales except in alcohol blends in five midwestern states, said, `` Our dealers set their own prices.'' In <LOCATION> Ashland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a midwestern marketer with 2,000 outlets, said leaded gasoline had been priced at or above unleaded regular `` for several months now'' at stations his company serves. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, the largest industry trade group, said in a statement that misfueling was declining and would continue to do so, and <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> should `` ensure that both the service station operator and the individual motorist are prevented from -LRB- engaging in -RRB- this practice.''
