<HEAD>Liggett Introduces New Low-Price Cigarette</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday that it is introducing a new cigarette called Pyramid, which will be available to retailers at carton prices comparable to those of 1980. <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> executives say Pyramid represents a new low-price category that is a departure from the direction the tobacco industry has been taking. `` Cigarette prices have climbed fairly steadily since 1981, with the primary reason being the major excise tax increase by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> A. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. The difference between the price of generic cigarettes and full-price cigarettes is narrowing, he said, and the company felt the time was right to establish a third tier of cigarettes. `` What we're going to offer smokers who are showing this clear preference for branded-price-value cigarettes is the ability to buy a quality product using their 1988 purchasing power at early 1980 prices _ that's what the Pyramid is all about,'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said. He said the savings to consumers could range from $ 2.50 to $ 5 per carton, depending on the state in which it is bought or the price of the brand that it is being compared against. The cigarette industry today is as competitive as it was in the early 1980s, <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said, and <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION>, the smallest of the six major cigarette manufacturers, has to be innovative. `` When faced with growing marketing pressures we began looking for non-conventional ways to counter big-spending efforts by the majors,'' he said. `` We ca n't outspend them, so we try and out-innovate them with another new category.'' The company began shipping Pyramid cigarettes on Monday.
